column52: I was definitely most surprised at how much emphasis was being placed on engineering design, linear signals/systems, and coding/software projects rather than diving a deeper in the biological and medical side of things. We only got one course in cell biology, chemistry, and anatomy/physiology with only very high-level medical applications given in other courses. This did make me think for a while that I should have gone into Nanotechnology Engineering. In hindsight, however, I can see the need for that design of the program so that we can graduate with the fundamentals to actually systematically work between the body and engineering technologies. I think I've long since realized that getting deeper into the actual "biomedical" part of Biomedical Engineering means going for graduate studies.
